googleReviewsBySlug.json.name: George Evans
googleReviewsBySlug.json.text:
So a few years ago, we called them out to inspect our septic system before we bought our home.  We were given a clean bill of health and told we were good to go, they pumped it, and we moved on.  Couldn't tell whose name was on the inspection report, initials look like M.H.

Fast-forward to present day, our pump is not running.  I make the call to them and they send a tech out (they responded very quickly and the tech that came out, Joey, was informative and helpful).  He told us that the pump was not plugged into the float switch correctly and because of this, the motor had burned up.  This was not mentioned on our buyer's inspection before we purchased the house.  I went ahead and had them replace the pump (which was quite expensive).  When asked if they could do anything on their price because their original inspection failed to identify what seemed like a pretty easy catch, they were pretty accusatory as if we were trying to dodge paying our bill.  They asked questions about whether landscapers (we don't have any) or anyone else would have changed the way the plug was plugged in (definitely did not happen).  Shame on me for not doing my research and making sure the plug was installed correctly when we bought the house, but I feel that they should have caught this and obviously they felt as if they would have if it had been that way when they made their initial inspection.  They have a good reputation with others in the neighborhood so I would probably give them another chance but I remain pretty unhappy with the miss on the initial inspection.  As far as the install today went, I guess time will tell.  The outdoor outlet that the pump is plugged into was left zip-tied closed and seems like it is smashing the pump plug/wire.  Hopefully this doesn't cause more issues down the road.
